# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on November 26, 1788, for the 1st Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature ratified the Constitution on December 12, 1787, by a vote of 46–23.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of senators and representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature scheduled the election for November 26, 1788, and provided for it to be held on an at-large basis.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was an attempt by the Federalist-dominated legislature to prevent anti-Federalist Representatives from being elected in frontier districts.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Both parties submitted tickets with 8 candidates each.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The large German population in Pennsylvania tended to vote for German candidates, giving the Anti-Federalist Muhlenberg and Hiester enough votes to gain seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Elections to the United States House of Representatives were held in Pennsylvania on Tuesday, October 11, 1791, for the 2nd Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Six Pro-Administration and two Anti-Administration Representatives had been elected on an at-large basis in the previous election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The elections in Pennsylvania were the last elections held for the 2nd Congress, out of the states that were in the Union at the start of the Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The previous election had been held at-large, but for the 2nd Congress, Pennsylvania divided itself up into 8 districts.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Note: Many of these counties covered much larger areas in 1791 than they do today, having since been divided into smaller counties.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Five incumbents (3 Anti-Administration and 2 Pro-Administration) ran for re-election, four of whom won.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The incumbents George Clymer (P) and Henry Wynkoop (P) of the 2nd district and Thomas Scott (P) of the 8th district did not run for re-election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Muhlenberg switched from Pro-Administration to Anti-Administration.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Four Pro-Administration and four Anti-Administration candidates were elected, a net gain of 2 seats for the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Election data are incomplete for the 1st and 2nd districts and are missing for the 4th and 5th districts.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1800–01 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 29, 1800, and August 1, 1801.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 7th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1801.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were held at the same time as the 1800 presidential election, in which Vice President Thomas Jefferson, a Democratic Republican, defeated incumbent President John Adams, a Federalist.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 106 seats, representing 15 states.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These elections resulted in the Democratic-Republicans picking up 22 seats from the Federalists.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This brought the Democratic-Republicans a solid majority of 68 seats, whereas the Federalists were only able to secure 38.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Many state legislatures also changed to Democratic-Republican control, with the result that many new Democratic-Republicans were voted into the Senate.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists never again succeeded in gaining a majority of seats in the House of Representatives, and the national Federalist Party disintegrated completely in the early 1820s.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The victory of Jefferson and the Democratic-Republicans can be attributed partially to unpopular policies pursued by the Adams administration, including the Alien and Sedition Acts, which sought to curtail guarantees of freedom of speech and freedom of the press spelled out in the Bill of Rights.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The difference between Federalist policies in support of a strong national government and the Democratic-Republican preference for states' rights played a prominent role in the election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Federal taxation became an issue as Southerners and Westerners rejected federal taxes levied on property.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1800 and 1801 during the 6th United States Congress and 7th United States Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by date then district.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Note: Between the two sources used, there is disagreement over the ordering of the candidates.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are ordered here as Goddard and Talmadge in 8th and 9th place as it is more likely that they'd been at the top of the runners-up given that they were subsequently elected to fill vacancies in the 7th Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election, which was not met in the 1st and 6th districts, necessitating a second trial.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In 1800, New Jersey returned to its traditional at-large district, continued to use this system to select representatives until it was abolished in 1842, with a single exception in 1813.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island switched to a general ticket for its two seats, instead of electing each one separately.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only one candidate received a majority in the 1800 election, requiring an 1801 run-off election to choose a Representative for the second seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law required a candidate to win a majority to take office, necessitating a run-off election in the 2nd (Eastern) district.
